@nicholasbishop you're not being a pain in the ass, we are definitely behind on documentation and with holidays coming up many of us are currently getting killed with work deadlines (I know I am).  Pipenv shells are generally fine, but they probably shouldn't be used in production.  The reason there isn't much documentation for `pipenv run` is just because there isn't much to document so it probably never occurred to us/we never got around to it.

The command consumes everything after it and acts like you ran it in an activated virtualenv for your project.  This basically just means you never have to activate virtual environments in order to run code, so you don't have to worry about which virtual environment you are in, whether you deactivated, etc.  This is the main reason why pipenv uses the project name + a hash of its absolute path as a deterministic name for the virtualenv it creates, so that when you run `pipenv run` inside the directory structure pipenv knows exactly where to find the relevant virtualenv and execute in that context.

Basically, if you call `pipenv run somescript.py` it is similar to calling `/path/to/virtualenv/python somescript.py`, except pipenv provides additional convenience such as loading your `.env` file into the environment and such.  This way you can context switch or directory switch or, in your editor, instead of constantly sourcing virtualenvs, prefix all your commands with `pipenv run` and it will figure things out for you.  It's not that you're not _supposed_ to do things inside a pipenv shell, because really, its fine.  Kenneth uses the fish plugin for pipenv shells, so I'm pretty sure he makes heavy use of that feature.  It's really just that you lose some of the benefits when you do that.

