For memory, i found a 'quick and dirty' workaround for this problem (just to be able to save in database a new object from proxy class). I declare a modelForm associated with my 'proxy' Inline, and then override save() method to cast to the right subclass. Seems to do the work so far. 
So with this solution, drop down menu to select subclass display the baseclass verbose_name , so if there is more than one direct proxy subclass, this workaround may not be easy to deal with..still I can now save my proxy models in admin.

```python
class TextParamForm(forms.ModelForm):
    class Meta:
        model = TextParam
        exclude = ['order']

    def save(self, commit=True):
        self.instance.__class__ = TextParam
        return super(TextParamForm, self).save(commit)
...
class SubmitInputsInline(StackedPolymorphicInline):
    ...
    class TextParamInline(PolymorphicInputInlineChild):
        model = BaseParam
        exclude = ['order']
        form = TextParamForm
   ...
...
```

